BONUS : Calculating Variance and Std Deviation¶

Variance is a measure of variability in statistics. It assesses the average squared difference between data values and the mean. Unlike some other statistical measures of variability, it incorporates all data points in its calculations by contrasting each value to the mean.

https://statisticsbyjim.com/basics/variance/

When there is no variability in a sample, all values are the same, and the variance equals zero. As the data values spread out further, variability increases.

For example, these two distributions have the same mean. However, the dataset on the right has greater variability and, hence, a higher variance.

To Calculate the Variance manually:

Interpreting the Variance The variance in statistics is the average squared distance between the data points and the mean. Because it uses squared units rather than the natural data units, the interpretation is less intuitive. Higher values indicate greater variability, but there is no intuitive interpretation for specific values. Despite this drawback, some statistical hypothesis tests use it in their calculations. For example, read about the F-test and ANOVA.

Squaring the differences serves several purposes.

Squaring the differences prevents values above and below the mean from canceling each other out. Consequently, variance is always greater than or equal to zero. It is almost always a positive value because only datasets containing one repeated value (e.g., all values equal 15) have a value of zero.

If you take the square root of the variance, you obtain the standard deviation, which does use the intuitive natural data units.

The standard deviation (SD) is a single number that summarizes the variability in a dataset. It represents the typical distance between each data point and the mean. Smaller values indicate that the data points cluster closer to the meanthe values in the dataset are relatively consistent. Conversely, higher values signify that the values spread out further from the mean. Data values become more dissimilar, and extreme values become more likely.

Understanding the standard deviation is crucial. While the mean identifies a central value in the distribution, it does not indicate how far the data points fall from the center. Higher SD values signify that more data points are further away from the mean. In other words, extreme values occur more frequently.

Variability is everywhere. When you order a favorite meal at a restaurant, it isnt exactly the same each time. Your drive time to work varies every day. Parts from an assembly line might seem identical, but they have subtly different lengths and widths.

When variability is high, you can expect to experience extreme values more frequently, which can cause problems! If the restaurant meal differs noticeably from the usual, you might not like it at all. When your morning commute takes much longer than the average travel time, you will be late. And, manufactured parts that are too far out of spec wont perform correctly.

https://statisticsbyjim.com/basics/standard-deviation/

Example of Using the Standard Deviation Suppose two pizza restaurants advertise a 20-minute average delivery time. Were starving and both look equally good! However, we know the mean does not tell the entire story!

Lets assess their standard deviations to choose the restaurant. Imagine we obtain their delivery time data. One restaurant has a SD of 10 minutes while the other has a value of 5. How does this affect deliveries?

The graphs below incorporate the SDs to answer this question. The restaurant with the larger standard deviation (10 minutes) has more variable delivery times and a broader distribution curve.

In these charts, well consider a 30-minute wait or longer to be unacceptablewere hungry! The shaded areas represent the percentage of delivery times exceeding 30 minutes. Almost 16% of deliveries for the high variability pizza joint exceed 30 minutes compared to only 2% for the low variability restaurant. They both have a mean delivery time of 20 minutes, but I know where Id place my order when Im hungry!

I always recommend graphing your data in a histogram so you can see the variability. These charts really bring the SD to life!

How to Calculate Std Deviation:

  • When you have the sample vaiance ready with you , then take the Square of that:

Back to Bootcamp lecture:

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/18297906#overview

In [85]:
alcohol.var()
Out[85]:
5796.52561153286

Variance is simply the Average of Squared differences from the MEAN

For each observation, find its difference relative to the MEAN , then Square that difference and then find the SUM of all those differences for each observation. Then in the end divide the Sum of these Squared differences by "n" which is the "Number of Observations in the sample" MINUS 1 (n-1). this "-1" here is known as the Degrees of Freedom adjustment.

This is to say that there is only "n-1" degrees of Freedom in our sample. Which is to say that not all the observations in our sample have the Freedom to vary. Because the SUM of the Difference between each observation and the MEAN should equal to ZERO

So, if we know the Average and all the values except one of them, we could figure that one value our based on this fact alone and thats the reason why we divide by "n-1" here instead of n

Hence , this way the sample variance is adjusted for the right Degrees of Freedom , that is "n-1"

And finally the Sample Std Deviation is the Square Root of the Variance.

#Variance
alcohol.var()
Out[86]:
5796.52561153286

where() method¶

The where() method is not truly meant for filtering

  • This is a method which allows us to efficiently replace values where the given condition is False
  • This is how it works:
  • alcohol.where("Condition", "value to be replaced for x if condition is False")
In [191]:
alcohol.where(lambda x: x>200 , other = 'too small')

the map() method¶

Althogh map() method is technically used for substituting values right. We can take control of the substitution.

the functionality of apply() and map() is identical.

In [7]:
alcohol.map(lambda x:x**2)
Out[7]:

                ...

Zambia            16.0

Length: 193, dtype: float64
In [8]:
alcohol.map(np.square)
Out[8]:
country
Afghanistan        NaN
Albania         2916.0
Algeria          196.0
Andorra        97344.0
Angola          2025.0
                ...   
Venezuela          9.0
Vietnam            1.0
Yemen              NaN
Zambia            16.0
Zimbabwe          16.0
Length: 193, dtype: float64

But , when we get into the more complex transformations , for example : Callables and Parameters, map and apply are no longer substitutes (you cannot use map() for complicated transformations)

Example : This code will work with apply() but not with map()¶

alcohol.map(multiply_by_self_with_min , args = (200, ))¶

If our transformation is very specific and very Custom , we would want to stick with apply()

TRANSFORMS¶

We saw three methods to apply transformations¶

update()¶

Modifies series values in place using another Series.

Syntax : Series.update(other_Series)

apply()¶

Applies a function or a universal function (ufunc) or any custom function on each Series value .

apply() is most flexible

Example : Series.apply(np.sqrt)

map()¶

map() is technically a substitution function that substitutes series values with other values from a function or Series or Dictionary.

map() is definitely more flsexible in terms of input

It accepts various types of inputs

But apply() is more flexible in terms of various transformations. We can define any function. We can control what inputs that function takes as we apply the function using positional or keyword arguments

apply() is a great choice if we want to apply the transformation to the entire series.

example : series.map({'old_value' : 'new_value'})

There is some thing not clear about this approach . We really don't know how low or how high each observation is.

  • A more standard approach to this would be to calculate the "Standard Score" or "Z-score" , In a way we are standardising each observation by quantifying it in terms of deviation from the mean.

Z-Score¶

Z-Score is the number of Std Deviations that a given observation is being different from Sample MEAN

If the observation x is 10 and mean is 0 and we get a Z-score of 5 , we can say that the observation 10 is 5 std deviations away or above the mean of 0

In [35]:
#We create a new series called "Z-scores"
#We start with observations Minus their beers.mean divided by the Std deviation

z_scores = (beers - beers.mean()) / beers.std()
